Click on the figures for larger ones.

<h2>Ianos was the strongest medicane ever</h2>
<br><br>
Medicane Ianos, which hit the west and south of Greece on 18 and 19 September, was a special storm. It was the heaviest medicane ever -which was established after research- was mainly due to the very high sea surface temperature anomalies in the Mediterranean Sea over August and September.
<br><br>
The strongest gust eventually amounted to 54 meters per second, 108 knots or 194 kilometers per hour. The highest measured 1-minute mean of the wind (for hurricanes, instead of the standard 10-minute mean, a 1-minute mean is used) was 44 meters per second or 88 knots. This made Ianos a strong Category 2 hurricane at its peak.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/sep2020/Analyses_17_September_2020_12UTC.jpg"><img alt="" src="../images/sep2020/Analyses_17_September_2020_12UTC.jpg" width="250px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 1: Weather analyses on 17 September 12 UTC (source: KNMI)</em>
<br><br>
<br><br>
<a href="../images/sep2020/Ianos_2020-09-17_1140Z.jpg"><img alt="" src="../images/sep2020/Ianos_2020-09-17_1140Z.jpg" width="250px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 2: Satellite images from 17 September (source: NASA World view)</em>
<br><br>
Furthermore, in the wettest place, the unimaginable amount of 644 millimeters of rain fell. No wonder much of Central Greece was flooded after Ianos's passage. With these numbers it is now established that the medicane was the heaviest ever seen in the Mediterranean in modern times.
A long history preceded the creation of Ianos. It all started when a bubble of cold in the higher parts of the atmosphere near northeast Spain rose to the Mediterranean Sea around September 6. In no time an active disturbance formed that brought severe weather to the Balearic Islands. There was a lot of rain, sometimes with a strong wind and there was extensive flooding. In the days that followed the system moved to the east and also brought heavy showers to Corsica and Sardinia. Then it fell silent for a moment. The (weakened) bubble of cold air moved further to the southeast over the open sea and ended up in the sea area between Libya and Sicily. In that location, the circumstances for the development of a medicane were suddenly particularly favorable. There was peace in the air above and the sea water was more than warm enough for the medicane development, which indeed happened on September 16 and 17. Around the core of the evolving system, heavy thunderstorms began to revolve more and more clearly. Ultimately, the system, which had now been given four names, also got a clear eye in the middle. And finally it crossed the west and south of Greece on 18 and 19 September.
<br><br>
<h2>Specific climate indicators for September 2020</h2>
<br><br>
September 2020 was warmer than the 1981-2010 average for September over most parts of Europe (see Figure 6 and 7 below). Largest anomalies occurred in the East especially in countries bordering the Black Sea with anomalies above +3&deg;C, partly even +5&deg;C.
The exceptionally warm conditions in September in this region is also well illustrated by the indices related to maximum temperature. As visible from the number of summer days (days with max. temperature > 25&deg;C), the region bordering the Black Sea experienced more than 10 summer days more than normal, same over France.
Even more outstanding was the number of warm days, that is days with daily maximum temperatures above the 90th percentile (Fig. 4). All or almost all September days were within this high temperature range in the region bordering the Black Sea, for example parts of Ukraine, Romania, Moldavia, Bulgaria and Turkey, but also over parts of France.
